description.plain: Maisie described the song, “I wrote ‘Not Another Rockstar’ about my very debatable track record with men. The song aims to make fun of me and my decisions and them and their guitars, and it feels right that I wrote it with Ines who is my best friend because she was literally rolling her eyes at every line like ‘too real’. I hope everyone comes out of this song realising the true rockstar was in fact me. Obviously. No longer the rockstar’s girlfriend, we are the whole rockstar these days, girls.”

description.plain:
“Body Better” is the the lead single of Maisie Peters' second album The Good Witch.

When the song was announced Peters said of the song:

It’s a song about vulnerability and quiet, forbidden fury; about heartbreak and insecurity so deeply rooted you have no idea where it begins or ends.

In her Glamour magazine essay written about the song, Peters explained that the song was written after a breakup, about the insecurity she felt that lead her to compare herself to an ex’s new partner.

Everything I felt insecure about, all the reasons I could imagine that he had decided he didn’t want me, I now had a perfect example of someone who I could tell myself was the opposite.

She goes on to say:

I wrote this song about vulnerability and how it stings when it’s used against you – about my relationship with my body.

annotations: Is her body better than mine

The repetition of this lyric, especially in the bridge is meant to represent intrusive thoughts.

In an interview with the Rolling Stone Maisie described the song as coming from “an ugly thought about a recent time she compared her body to another girl’s, deeming it hotter, categorically better."

Then I, I can’t help thinking that she’s got a better body
 Has she got a body better than mine?

In an exclusive essay with Glamour, Peters explained the context with which she wrote this lyric:


Something I wrote on my iPhone notes, late at night when the most spidery of thoughts come to me. I had gone through a breakup of sorts a few months before, when I’d felt a great deal for someone who I thought felt the same for me. In a tale as old as time, he sadly did not.

There’s nothing like heartbreak to make you magnify yourself with the most poisonous of lenses.

All the clothes and the warning signs
 How’s it feel to have made me cry?

In a Q&A about the song on twitter, Peters described the lyric as her favourite.

description.plain:
“Blonde” was announced for release, via an official Instagram post from Maisie on the 28th July. It is part of a joint release, alongside the song “Good Enough”, which Maisie has dubbed ‘sister songs’.

blonde out the 5th august, and good enough out the 19th august. two sisters songs that represent the two sides of the same feeling, of my artistry, of a breakup, of my heart. i wrote blonde a few months ago and good enough a few years ago, but when i stumbled upon the good enough demo in my notes app it felt just as relevant, almost like past me wrote it for me this year. you haven’t heard it yet, but u will. i love both songs so much and it felt like one without the other didn’t make sense , so i decided u guys could just have both :)) are u a blonde girl or a good enough girl i guess u will have to wait and see"


Maisie Peters via Instagram .

annotations: And I kissed your friends ’cause your friends said you kissed her

Her ex’s friends are claiming that he cheated, we don’t know for sure that he did. Also, with this line being after him “pulling the trigger”, it’s likely the two were already broken up, and therefore it isn’t cheating. Still, as a means of revenge, she kissed his friends.

Interestingly, this line could also be heard and interpreted as “all of the others, can sell out each other”.

annotations:
You kept me as your favourite secret
 And I thought we just took it slow

Maisie is establishing from the beginning that she’s the “side chick” and not his main priority. He’s gaslit her into thinking that he just wants to take their relationship day-by-day (i.e., not posting her on his social media), but in actuality, he’s hiding her from his friends / family because he’s involved with someone else.
You’re losing your mind
Another reference to Patrick Bateman…throughout both the novel and movie, it’s unclear whether or not Patrick is actually committing these crimes, or if he’s gone insane.
All kinds of ghosts down in your basement

Patrick Bateman’s whole deal is that he’s a serial killer with both metaphorical and literal skeletons in his closet. In the movie, one of his victims comes across multiple female corpses while trying to escape.

They said your girlfriend’s from the beaches
 It’s funny how everybody but me knows

Maisie’s ex had another girlfriend while dating her – hence the breakup.

Everybody knows about his girl ‘from the beaches’ but Maisie, which implies she is not the favourite in the several relationships he has – one could suggest that Maisie played the role of her ex’s ‘side-chick’.
[Chorus]

The chorus is similar to the first half of the bridge to Maisie’s song You to You

I know this song is bitter but my calls didn’t get through to you
Blocked on both your phones, oh, look at that, I guess it’s two for two
Calling me a psycho to our friends and that’s not news to me
Wish it was but honestly, it’s just so you
I feel like you feel nothing, that’s fine

The song ‘Volcano’ on this album states similar lyrics. The narrator sings:

All or nothing, you chose nothing

which is similar to these lines.
I feel like you feel nothing, that’s fine

This is a parallel with Maisie’s song ‘Volcano’, which has the lyrics:
“All or nothing, you felt nothing”
Crazy to think that you still call me psycho

Maisie first mentioned a partner calling her a “psycho” in 2018 in her song You to You:

Calling me a psycho to our friends

This line could represent how it’s been so long, yet they are still calling her a “psycho”. There are two ways to interpret this line, though:
Crazy to think that you still call me ‘psycho’
and
Crazy to think that you still call me, psycho

Baby, who has two phones?
 One for her and one to still call me psycho

A reference/callback to a lyric in You to You from Maisie’s first EP:

“Blocked on both your phones, oh, look at that, I guess it’s two for two
Calling me a psycho to our friends and that’s not news to me”

Calling me a hundred times
 Time you drew a line
 And stopped wasting mine

Obviously, she means that this man keeps calling her, so by stating that he should draw a line, it would mean to stop calling her. By saying stopped wasting mine, she is playing with the meaning of the word. The specific definition for ‘line’ in ‘stopped wasting mine’ should be a telephone connection or service.

description.plain:
Despite all of his wrongdoings, Maisie sarcastically describes a one-sided relationship, full of toxicity and tragedy, where she keeps allowing him back. She doesn’t necessarily attack or express hatred towards herself nor her partner, but rather emphasizes her willingness to overlook his infidelity and carelessness in order to keep him by her side at all costs.

Maisie proposes an innovative take on toxic relationships. Her listing of the ridiculous sacrifices she’s making serves as a wake-up call to people tangled up in such relationships. There’s no reason to be entangled in such circumstances, no matter how much love they have.

Maisie released this song following a six month hiatus, due to her being busy with school and exams:

I know I’ve been away a while (final year of A levels + writing looooooots of sick new songs called for me) but I have PLANS I tell u PLANS for the next few months which I hope you will loooove.

“Worst of you” is the first song Maisie released under the record label “Atlantic Records UK”. She released her previous two tracks “Places we were made” and “Birthday” independently in 2017.

annotations: So give me your worst excuses, any reason to stay
She will take any excuse because she wants the relationship to continue, even if it hurts her

But baby, the truth is I make your excuses
 You let me down and I’m used to it
She has gotten used to the cycle of the relationship disappointing her that she gives excuses for her partner to use because she can’t let go of them

We make up, but I know we’ll fistfight
 Through iPhones, my left hook a no-show
 ’Cause I’ll just keep letting you win
Even after the apologies and excuses are accepted, arguments reignite through text and Maisie would win except she allows her partner to win to them as a way to keep them in the relationship

Give me your lips that taste of her, I’d kiss them again
 I’d rather you walk all over me than walk away

Here, Maisie describes knowing that her significant other has been with someone else. But the added “I’d kiss them again” shows that Maisie will put up with the infidelity. That she would let this person be with someone else if it meant she could still be with them.
“I’d rather you walk all over me than walk away”, shows Maisie’s undying commitment to a person who is clearly treating her awfully. The toxic relationship is somehow justified through Maisie’s rose-coloured glasses, she just wants them to stay.

So let me drown, I’ll be there with the band
 Hit the sea bed, all I’d see is you

This line is a possible reference to the 1997 film Titanic, a tragic love story based on the great RMS Titanic. In the film, the Titanic’s band continued to play music as the ship is sinking to its doom, in hopes of calming the passengers down as a final act of heroism.



Maisie considers the devotion shown to her lover like the Titanic’s band, a heroic and honorable display of love.

It is often in their final moments that people experience the “deathbed phenomena”. Maisie believes her boyfriend would be her last vision before death following her great sacrifice. Being her last vision proves Maisie is head over heels for her boyfriend, despite his inconsiderate and bad treatment.

Another night, another dotted line
 I sign my heart away to you
 Some call it foolish, guess I’ll call it art

Maisie portrays her relationship as a one-sided arrangement. She’s sacrificing so much in return for nothing but temporary highs and pain avoidance.

Similar to objectivity in art, Maisie considers other’s opinions to be more than just opinions, because she can continue to be with someone she deeply cares about regardless of the specifics. It is rather a radical subjective viewpoint on toxic love.

It’s worth noting that Maisie believes her dysfunctional relationship, which is fraught with infidelity and mistreatment, to be a piece of art rather than what it is, highlighting the extent to which people can go to justify toxic and abusive relationships.

You role-play the good guy, lemon juice your white lies
 But I see ’em in the sunrise
Just to clarify it is definitely ‘lemon juice’ not ‘induce’ afraid to say I did write the song so I do know these things x

You role-play the good guy, lemon juice your white lies
 But I see ’em in the sunrise
Just to clarify it is definitely ‘lemon juice’ not ‘induce’ afraid to say I did write the song so I do know these things x

Lemon juice can be used as material to write on a white paper, becoming invisible shortly after, and for that, it is referred to as “invisible ink”. The writing appears once directed to heat (in this case, sunlight) as pale brown on the paper.

Maisie uses “invisible ink” as a metaphor for the lies and deception her boyfriend uses. He masks care and affection when it’s convenient, but Maisie sees through his deception, especially when she’s not consumed by his love, and is seeing clearly.

description.plain:
“I’m Trying (Not Friends)” is a song originally written for season 2 of Apple TV+ comedy Trying, originally  set to premiere 21 May 2021. Peters decided it wasn’t the vibe, calling it “chaotic, bitchy, and passive-aggressive, and really flawed” for Apple Music. A fast-paced, lyrically dynamic song, it sees Peters insisting that at least she’s trying to be friends with her ex, while her ex is not.

In an interview with TapeNotes podcast, she mentioned that she originally wrote the first verse for Apple TV+ show Music from Insecure, which she released a few months before You Signed Up For This, but realized that the song suited her life more as she continued to write.

annotations:
’Cause you’re seeing someone pretty and I hate her guts
 So I’ll be telling you she’s nice on the bus home
These lines set the tone that Maisie is not a reliable narrator in this relationship. She is determined to please her ex-partner by supporting his choices even when they hurt her.
One for being obsessed with someone who puts you secondary
This is the first time in the song that Maisie admits that she is the one in the relationship that is holding on despite not being treated with the respect that she deserves.

If I’m being frank, I want a “sorry” but I’ll settle for a handshake
 ’Cause I’m the baby but I’m gonna be the bigger man, babe

In reference to the earlier line, “being obsessed with someone who puts you secondary”, we can now assume that Maisie has not swallowed her pride and is determined to perceive herself as the winner of this relationship. By doing so, she gives herself permission to stay in it as she is proving them wrong. She has given them many chances and is in the sunk-cost fallacy of believing there must be some positive outcome to all the time and effort she has put into the relationship.

And I swore that I’d swallow my pride
 And you swore you would do better this time
 Well, I might be bitter and twisted and broken and petty and lying

The appearance of a consensus in these lines contradicts the concessions of each individual in the relationship.

It shows that the narrator (Maisie) has conceded to “swallow my pride”, implying she will be more open to accepting the behavior of the partner in this conversation. To swallow her pride in this sense is to accept when she doesn’t get what she wants.

The partner has conceded to “do better this time”. However, they have also secured the concession from Maisie to accept when they don’t do better, implying that her expectations are prideful and uncalled for.

She agrees to these terms despite not believing them because she is not yet ready to let go of the relationship.

But at least I’m trying
 At least I’m trying
 At least I’m trying

In an interview with the podcast Tape Notes, Peters' and co-writer Jo Rubel explained that the song was originally written for the soundtrack album she wrote for the TV show Trying before deciding that it didn’t fit.

The sound world that [the Trying] soundtrack exists in is not, it’s very different sounding.
— Joe Rubel, via Tape Notes

In the original demo written Peters' showed a “more positive spin” with the lyrics “At least we’re trying”. However, with the change to the final version she explained:

In that context with this song it’s kind of passive aggressive, it’s actually not how [it originally] sounded at all.
Got friends, got at least a healthy five

Maisie lives with 5 other women in a shared flat, as mentioned in title track You Signed Up For This

6 girls, on Alphabet Road
5'1", do you think I’ll grow anymore?
[Verse 2]

In an interview for the tapenotes podcast with Joe Rubel, Maisie’s producer, Maisie shared a voice memo from November 10, 2020 sent to Joe at 1AM with the original second verse, which she called “not the right second verse”

After “Just me? Ok” the original verse branched off into:

So you grew your hair out
Swear they get over me and always fucking grow their hair out
And that actress liked your photo and I shouldn’t care now
Think I’m spiralling, the fair is at the fairground

https://open.spotify.com/episode/226FgBGu5DDUXFP8K4owr2?si=0ee0b61628eb4682
Not friends, no, we’re somewhere in between
On TikTok, Maisie said this song is the perfect anthem for a “situationship” and this lyric speaks to this where they are somewhere in between friendship and a relationship.
One for calling guys with guitars in a cemetery
Peters stated on her Instagram Story this line refers to Mile End Cemetery
So many blank slates I could build a whole fucking house
Maisie has mentioned this being one of her favourite lyrics from the album

annotations:
No one ever taught me the protocol
 What do you do when the good guys change their mind?

Coincidentally, this lyric is remarkably similar to one from Taylor Swift’s “happiness”:

No one teaches you what to do
When a good man hurts you

Though Maisie is a big fan of Taylor Swift, she wrote “Good Enough” in January 2020 before ever hearing the song.

https://twitter.com/maisiehpeters/status/1560529160111636480

I never said I was perfect
 Like you

In an Instagram story on August 19, 2022, Maisie said, “that line is so hurtful . like sometimes i hear it and it sounds so bitter and sarcastic and then other times it sounds so hopeless and like u truly genuinely believe they are perfect, even after everything they put you through.”
You’d bury me someday

In an Instagram story on August 19, 2022, Maisie said, “i like the double meaning of this line ! like the sweet one being that u thought you’d die still together, and the pain meaning being that deep down u always subconsciously knew you’d be broken and buried by them.”
But I’ll sit in your favourite dress and wonder how you’ve been

This chorus slightly changes the earlier line:

But I’ll sit in your favorite dress and ask you where you’ve been

She used to be able to ask him where he was, but now that they’ve parted ways, she can only wonder how he’s doing. Add to this the fact that Maisie is still sitting in his “favourite dress” despite the breakup, implies that she is unable to move on from their relationship and the mental implications it had on her.
’Cause if I couldn’t be one, I wouldn’t ever be two

There are a couple ways to interpret this line. In an Instagram story on August 19, 2022, Maisie described it as “when u know there is literally no role left for u in that persons life.” Another possible meaning is that she doesn’t want to settle for being his second choice.



Alternatively, it could mean that Maisie thinks if she isn’t good enough on her own, she’s unworthy to be part of a couple. This ideology is perpetrated by the common phrase, “If you can’t love yourself, you can’t love anyone else.”

There were four eyes in the garden
 Two cried, but two looked down
“Moments I Didn’t Feel Good Enough,” a poem Maisie wrote inspired by this song, contains a very similar line: “the garden, when two eyes cried (and two just looked down).”
But I’ll sit in your favourite dress and ask you where you’ve been

This is reminiscent of a line from Maisie’s poem, “Moments I Didn’t Feel Good Enough,” which says, “the night I wore the dress that used to stop somebody mid sentence.”

It also parallels a lyric from her 2018 song “In My Head”:

Wearing the dress that I met you in, sent you spinning

Also, wearing his “favourite dress” when he’s been out without her, could be a way of trying to get his attention back on her and trying to get him to fall in love with her again, reiterating the idea of not feeling “good enough”.

description.plain:
This song is written about Maisie’s friend Cate Canning’s brother, after having met him at a Halloween party she hosted in 2021.
Before it’s release, and even it’s completion, Maisie leaked sections of the song on TikTok, only for it to go viral. Her fans became obsessed with the song and desperately wanted it to be released.
On Tuesday April 19, Maisie released a pre save link hinting that the song could be released soon.
Cate’s Brother was finally released on Friday 6th May 2022.

Nirvana were an American rock band that rose to fame in the early 90’s – suggesting he listens to music above his age range and is seen as more manly.

A dictionary definition of the word ‘nirvana’ is ‘a state of being perfect’, hinting that the situation Maisie finds herself in is perfect.
[Verse 2]
Maisie leaked this verse after the song got 20,000 presaves.
And now I date Cate’s brother

Maisie is not actually dating Cate’s brother, but he is a real person that she thanks for being a “good sport” about the song.
https://twitter.com/maisiehpeters/status/1522506155259572225
This final line was almost going to be “and now I hate Cate’s brother”, but she opted for a light-hearted vibe. This further confirms that the song’s story is made-up.
https://twitter.com/maisiehpeters/status/1522531024525217792
He’s 6 foot 2 and a little younger than me

Maisie tweeted that this line was ‘giving he’s younger than my exes but he acts like such a man so’, a lyric from Taylor Swift’s …Ready For It? Maisie is known to be a big T Swift fan.
https://twitter.com/maisiehpeters/status/1520079913570680832

”Are you gonna work, you gonna hurt
 You gonna last forever?”
 ”Are we gonna make it, gonna break it
 When it’s now or never?”
 ”If it’s gonna hurt, will it be worth it?
 And will I recover?”
 “Are you gonna feel the way I feel?”
 Are you for real, Cate’s brother?

The chorus shows Maisie’s hesitation before getting into a relationship with him – she has her guard up as to not get herself hurt. The line, ‘you gonna hurt’, captures her feeling as if Cate’s brother might break up with her, causing great heartache/hurt.

You said, ”Get a flight to Canada
 And you can meet my mother”
Cate Canning, whose brother the song is allegedly about, lives in Canada.
Cate had had family stay from Canada
Cate Canning, whose brother the song is about, is originally from Vancouver, Canada.
Cate and Tommy showed up
“Cate and Tommy” refers to singer Cate Canning (whose brother the song is about) and the band Tommy Lefroy, made up of Wynter Bethel and Tessa Mouzourakis.

I threw this Halloween party
 And I invited forty of my best friends

Maisie explained on Twitter in April 2022:

it was a party and all my housemates and I invited people and we barely got to 40 so it was an in joke of us desperately trying to have enough friends to fill a party tehe
